After reflecting the point $(3,4)$ in the $x$-axis, the $x$-coordinate of the image will be the same as the $x$-coordinate of the original point, $x=3.$ The original point is a distance of $4$ from the $x$-axis. The image will be the same distance from the $x$-axis, but below the $x$-axis.  Thus, the image has $y$-coordinate $-4.$ The coordinates of the image point are $\boxed{(3,-4)}.$ [asy]
draw((-5.5,0)--(5.5,0),linewidth(1));
draw((-5.5,0)--(5.5,0),EndArrow);
draw((0,-5.5)--(0,5.5),EndArrow);
draw((0,-5.5)--(0,5.5),linewidth(1));
draw((-5,-5)--(-5,5)--(5,5)--(5,-5)--cycle);
draw((-4,-5)--(-4,5));
draw((-3,-5)--(-3,5));
draw((-2,-5)--(-2,5));
draw((-1,-5)--(-1,5));
draw((1,-5)--(1,5));
draw((2,-5)--(2,5));
draw((3,-5)--(3,5));
draw((4,-5)--(4,5));
draw((-5,-4)--(5,-4));
draw((-5,-3)--(5,-3));
draw((-5,-2)--(5,-2));
draw((-5,-1)--(5,-1));
draw((-5,1)--(5,1));
draw((-5,2)--(5,2));
draw((-5,3)--(5,3));
draw((-5,4)--(5,4));
dot((3,4));
label("$x$",(5.5,0),E);
label("$y$",(0,5.5),N);
label("$(3,4)$",(3,4),NE);
draw((3,4)--(3,-4),dotted+linewidth(1));
dot((3,-4));
label("$(3,-4)$",(3,-4),NE);
[/asy]

We first determine where the lines $y=-2x+8$ and $y = \frac{1}{2}x-2$ cross the line $x=-2.$

For the line $y=-2x+8,$ when $x=-2,$ $y=-2(-2)+8=12,$ so the point of intersection is $(-2,12).$

For the line $y=\frac{1}{2}x-2,$ when $x=-2,$ $y=\frac{1}{2}(-2)-2=-3,$ so the point of intersection is $(-2,-3).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.2inch);
draw((-8,0)--(15,0),black+linewidth(1));
draw((-8,0)--(15,0),EndArrow);
draw((0,-8)--(0,15),black+linewidth(1));
draw((0,-8)--(0,15),EndArrow);
draw((-2,-9)--(-2,16),black+linewidth(1));
draw((-3.5,15)--(8,-8),black+linewidth(1));
draw((-8,-6)--(8,2),black+linewidth(1));
label("$y$",(0,15),N);
label("$x$",(15,0),E);
label("$x=-2$",(-2,-9),S);
label("$C(4,0)$",(3,-2),S);
label("$y=\frac{1}{2}x-2$",(8,2),NE);
label("$y=-2x+8$",(8,-8),SE);
label("$A(-2,12)$",(-2,12),SW);
label("$B(-2,-3)$",(-2,-3),NW);
[/asy]

Therefore, we can think of $\triangle ABC$ as having base $AB$ of length $12-(-3)=15$ and height being the distance from $C$ to the line segment $AB,$ or $4-(-2)=6.$

Therefore, the area of $\triangle ABC$ is $\frac{1}{2}(15)(6)=\boxed{45}.$
